,Recommended,512220,31356298,Posted: 25 April,all,Arcade Coin,"I have seen Trickster on Steam quite a few times, and I always thought it looked like just another SWING THE SWORD, KILL THE BADIE, MOVE ON type of game, but it really is quite more than that. It is really fun, and there is a TON to offer here. It's not a game you sit down (or in this case stand up) and beat in one sitting. I am currently a little over an hour and a half into it (my first play) and I am shocked at how much there really is here. The enemies are all very unique and can easily be differentiated from one another on the battlefield. I feel like the archers are a bit strong, but that just goes to show that there is a good challenge here. I found myself dying more than once simply because I did not handle the situation correctly, and that's significantly better than dying because of ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t enemies. It's a great game, and an amazing VR title. I would recommend to anyone!"
,Recommended,512220,33648932,Posted: 19 July,all,Conargle,"TL:DR - Straight up fun. 9/10 and a great addition to any VR games library.4 different movement types to choose from, i personally go for teleportation and a mix of locomotion/turning because i have a small play area. I can sprint around with one vive touchpad and use the other to turn either a set amount of continuously like a thumbstick (which does invoke a bit of motion sickness in me, but its well worth it for being able to fine tune the direction you're running in without having to turn your body if you're limited for space like me) but then i use the teleport as a form of quick dash to escape enemies closing in on me.Each weapon has a special ability which you charge up by doing damage, you can have 2 in your loadout. the dual crossbows is my favourite by far and the reloading feels amazingly satisfying. In fact the weapons in general are amazingly satisfying, an upward swing to the chin with a sword will send most unarmored enemies flying after a perfectly timed block. Alternatively, you could just stand in front of an enemy with your shield up and just wiggle your sword in their face for cheap shots.Did i mention enemies are armored? and its not just a visual thing, you need to swing at their fleshy parts if you want to use a sword. if youre a bow user and they have a helmet, then its really satisfying getting that headshot through the gap in their faceplates.Throwing weapons are a thing, you get an infinite amount with a cooldown like a special ability. my favourite are the 3 throwing knives positioned at the front of your waist as if tucked into a belt. you throw all 3 at once in a fan shape and it makes me feel like a rogue/assassin. I've also seen a magic bomb/potion type thing on another player but i havent unlocked it myself yet. It looks fun though.Graphically, i love the style of it, and supersampling keeps it really sharp and clean to look at at, even distant objects.The levels are technically randomly selected rather than ""generated"". Each level has specific tilesets that are chosen at random and connected together differently each time you load a level, a bit like the levels in warframe for example.The difficulty seems pretty balanced so far, Some levels harder than others because the difficulty is level based rather than a single setting you pick at the beginning of the game.Each difficulty make the enemies tougher and i think spawning more of them. This difficulty is then scaled further when you have more people playing together like in Diablo.There are unique boss type enemies which, unlike normal grunts that only... grunt, the bosses will talk♥♥♥♥♥♥and be all intimidating which is amusing to hear at a distance when you're closing in on them and killing all their minions.I can't speak too much for multiplayer, the most expirience i've had with that was when i was playing solo and some guy joined me halfway through a level and stuck around for a few more. He had unlocked more weapons than me and was clearly more experienced, however it doesn't throw off game balance at all as theres no leveling system that im aware of. he may have had different weapons but in terms of damage output, he was equally as useful as i was, making the combat more skill based than just being overpowered and destroying everything.Reviving dead teammates in multiplayer is a pretty tough thing. If you die mid-fight then you're probably dead for the rest of that encounter. You revive by holding your trigger over the teammates body and it fills up a meter. Which is pretty tough to do if you're being rushed by enemies. However, i have managed to do it when fighting against only archers. You just hide behind your shield blocking all arrows and revive them that way.Side note: the bar doesn't decay or lose progress at all if you stop reviving so the skilled player could probably run circles around the enemy, leading them away, then coming back to revive, then leading them away, then coming back to finish the revive. It doesn't take long at all to revive someone, but the enemy move surprisingly fast.The only issue i've encountered so far, are the various Ballistas generated in the world. Sometimes they're in good positinos, other times not so much. Also, aiming them is a ♥♥♥♥♥ to deal with if you're playing in a small standing area like me, even with thumbstick like movements available. I decided to just give up and run circles around the enemies firing my crossbows at them instead for the first ""defend the area"" type section.Overall it's a solid underrated dungeon crawler, most VR games i feel are too expensive, with barely enough content to make your money worthwhile (the whole £1/$1 per hour of fun thing), But with this game being only £10, in theory that's 10 hours of fun, but im certain im going to play this for many many more, especially for the amount of content in it, especially since they're still updating it and adding more."
,Recommended,512220,29128969,Posted: 8 January,all,Rayeth,"One of the first games you should get when you've just finished installing your Vive!If you ever wanted to feel like Legolas, Gimmli or Aragorn then this game is for you.While it does not have anything that can be remotely compared to a narrative story, it is just ridiculously fun to slice, shoot and bash through the procedurally generated levels or ""sky islands"".It even has a ""survive a ton of waves"" mode.The controls, utilizing the standard motion controllers, are very intuitive in my opinion and you get to choose from I think currently 4 modes of locomotion/teleportation. I am almost completly immune to motion sickness and as such I can't really tell how good/bad it is but I think it is way better than other games at the moment.The enemy response is almost as good as in non-VR games and it really feels like you stab and slash your enemies. If you hit them from below with an upward-move you can send them flying, stabbing them in the head kills them instantly (with some exceptions, the Balrog wouldn't go down after one blow either). There are some quirks every now and then but I never encountered anything game breaking. Sometimes an enemy gets stuck inside a rock, but hey, that's where those pesky orcs belong!The weapon arsenal is fun to explore and try out. The different weapons offer new ways of playing the game, from the sword & shield warrior to the hammer swinging barbarian, you can pretty much play however, or whoever you want.For an EA-title this one does provide several hours of fun, way more than some finished titles present to you. We actually tried it as a party game, testing who could survive the wave mode the longest.Last but not least, the community around the game as well as the dev team seem to be really cool guys, as the game gets a lot of input from players and the devs actually listen to it.If you are still unsure: In any case it is worth a try! Steam refund system is there, but you won't need it here!"
