76561198038610388,Recommended,512220,29429733,Posted: 22 January,all,Krut,"First thing's first, I think this game is worth the price point. Anything I say from now to the end of this mini review should be taken with a pinch of salt because none of it is damning, especially for a game which hasn't made it out of Early Access as yet. This game is a lot of fun, has good drum beat music that switches you into battle mode and what sound design there is impresses (I would have liked it if beating the shield madesome kind of sound but hey ho).Orc AI could do with some work. Sometimes the orcs come to fight you, sometimes they just derp and stand stock-still for an easy kill. There have been occasions where an orc ran away from me only to then confront me again and I can't work out if that's him being all fearful like and trying to save his own skin (because he saw how many of his brethren I had slaughtered) or if it was AI not knowing what it should do. Orcs do get stuck in geometry and in falling states if they come in via balloon and happen to drop down onto the wrong spot. This one time I watched in awe as an orc landed on a bridge only to charge forward (and down) into the void below, so it's safe to say their pathfinding ability is like their IQs, on the low side.Every now and then I'll teleport too close to orcs then I'll find that I can't hit them, which is fair enough.I imagine that by playing in walk mode you can avoid getting too close to orcs altogether. I've had situations where I teleported a short distance away from orcs and all the ones I could see a moment ago had apparently despawned (and none of them had been killed).Teleporting behind myself and wherever else I could escape to has gotten me out of harm's way many times but I think there have been just as many times where I was hit in the crossfireand took unavoidable damage. What I'll have to try and do is teleport more intelligently byducking before teleporting or otherwise taking cover behind rocks and trees and architecturewhile also laying down covering fire.When it comes down to it though, this is also a numbers game.If there are too many orcs in an area, they will probably overwhelm you because 5 archersfiring on you in an area just teleported to is something only Neo could counter.I might git gud but at the moment it's fun to kill in inventive ways.Blind use of the ballista immediately springs to mind as one of the more satisfying waysyou can slay an orc in Trickster although the only limit on how fast you can kill orcsis the speed you nock an arrow at and the haste with whichyou throw knives from your waist.The weaponry is a good selection that makes it so that you're never totally between a rock and a hard place. If all else fails, then a quick flick of the throwing knives at your belt will usually mess them up. I'm still getting used to the first badass weapon pair that you unlock. Nailing the berserker orcs with a ranged weapon special attack is always a highlight.Enemy ragdolling is pretty funny when it happens and the enemy variety is about what I would expect for the levels I've gone through (only the first few btw). You can see an orc in one of the trailers have his head shot through a pillar, which isn't a bad thing per se but it could detract from your immersion, I don't know. I've scored headshots I shouldn't have been able to in this way. When my Dad played, he accidentally kept switching weapons and made it look as though he beat an orc to death with a bow+arrow rather than sword+board which was kinda funny.That's my two penn'orth and I actually put my money where my mouth is so hopefully you come to some sort of conclusion what to do with your dinero based on what I said here or a video review or something and decide to help these devs out with your hardearned cash."
