76561198048876713,Recommended,512220,30738045,Posted: 25 March,all,Jac Richardson,"I still don't recommend this game, but it has gotten allot better. They fixed my major complaints with movement. I didn't get stuck on geometry or teleport weirdly this time. Movement relative to facing direction is a huge improvement. There is now a teleportation icon, though it is a little awkward to do a stick click to use it. Now I can move around comfortably.As for gameplay, still a little shallow, but if you were just looking for an archery simulator with a little bit of movement, this is great. Though honestly, given how simple it is, a 12 dollar price tag is a little high. The approach of this game is more on the side is allot of playable content instead of a little exceptional content.Now the gameplay is still a little shallow, especially the sword play, but fixing that would be extremely difficult, as in the only obvious way to do it requires better hardware. As in, an omni directonal treadmill, a real sword and walls for resistance.For reference, the original review below.Its poor navigation mechanics stifle what might otherwise be an enjoyable game.First, I like that you tried to use the vignette feature, but you don't seem to understand why you use the vignette feature. Yes, for one it is to get rid of your peripheral vision, but that is not the MAIN point. the main point is to prevent you from seeing things moving past too quickly. Look at eagle flight. That always darkens when your turning, which is good since turning is uncomfortable. But it also darkens when you're next to something. So if some one walks sideways, you should actually shift the part you can see toward the direction your moving. That is, you should darken forward too.Also, maybe provide some smoother vignettes, so they are less noticable. In fact, if you could make it adapt to how close the scene is, that would be even better.Next, you don't seem to understand why we use teleport mechanics. The teleport should be a teleport, not a quick acceleration forward, then a quick acceleration to a stop. Thats actually more uncomfortable then smooth movement. Look at how robo-recall and farlands handle teleportation. That is how it should feel. Also, teleporting based on which direction our hands are facing is disorienting without an icon to indicate where we will teleport.Twin stick movement, where to begin. First, its buggy. With oculus touch, try walking forward then touching your face. If its like my experience, you will suddenly rush backward. Similarly, if you pount your right hand at your left while walking you rush back and left. This movement is fast enough it warps me under stairs. Not being able to walk while your shield is up seems weird as well.I don't know how that code is working, but it should be independant of hand motion. Walking should depend only on gaze direction, so this bug is baffling to me.Your twin stick movement also has a tendency to get stuck on rocks, so I have to physically walk to keep moving. If I never turn, this happens less, but obviously I want to turn. Your walking also is not as smooth as I would like. I would advise trying out windlands. Windlands has a fantastic walking mechanics. Take a lesson from them.Look, I like your premise, but the game is really hard to play without a comfortable movement mechanic."
